-live-1392x884.jpg 1392w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Steve-Lacy-live-1068x678.jpg 1068w" sizes="(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px" /></p><p><a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/steve-lacy">史蒂夫·莱西</a>回忆起他<a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/steve-lacy-smashes-fans-phone-and-storms-offstage-during-new-orleans-concert-3335765">在舞台上砸碎歌迷相机的</a>决定，并重申他拒绝向那些“音乐会礼仪”不好的人道歉。</p><ul><li><strong>阅读更多： <a href="https://www.nme.com/features/music-features/crowd-throwing-fans-musicians-injury-3465598">奶酪轮、灰烬和性玩具：请停止向流行歌星扔屎</a></strong></li></ul><p>该事件发生在去年十月他在新奥尔良的一场演出中，当时一名观众向他扔了一次性相机。当摄像机落在他旁边的舞台上时，这位美国歌手兼词曲作者开始摧毁它，并拒绝为此道歉。</p><p>现在，事件发生一年后，莱西在一次新的采访中再次回忆起那一刻，并坚称他拒绝为“礼仪”不佳的音乐会观众道歉。</p><p> “我不得不接受这些孩子就是这样，”他对<a href="https://variety.com/2023/music/news/steve-lacy-bad-habit-fame-sexuality-car-crash-interview-1235688277/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>《综艺》杂志</em></a>说道，这是他发表初步声明以来首次讨论这一事件。</p><p> “一开始我很生气——他们想要太多。 “你能做到这个吗？”、“你能做到那个吗？”、“我要把这个扔在这里给你”、“我爱你”......但我不认为他们这样做是错误的，“他添加。 “尽管有时这让我很恼火，但他们还很年轻。很多孩子——这是他们的第一场音乐会，所以他们甚至不知道音乐会礼仪是什么。” </p><blockquote class="tiktok-embed" cite="https://www.tiktok.com/@katloveshellokitty/video/7158325437448473899" data-video-id="7158325437448473899" data-embed-from="oembed" style="max-width: 605px;min-width: 325px;" ><section> <a target="_blank" title="@katloveshellokitty" href="https://www.tiktok.com/@katloveshellokitty?refer=embed">@katloveshellokitty</a></p><p>这太出乎意料了<a title="斯蒂韦拉西" target="_blank" href="https://www.tiktok.com/tag/stevelacy?refer=embed">#stevelacy</a> <a title="给你世界巡演" target="_blank" href="https://www.tiktok.com/tag/giveyoutheworldtour?refer=embed">#giveyoutheworldtour</a></p><p> <a target="_blank" title="♬ 原声 - kat" href="https://www.tiktok.com/music/original-sound-7158325435540196142?refer=embed">♬ 原声 – 凯特</a></section></blockquote><p><script async src="https://www.tiktok.com/embed.js"></script></p><p> 这一事件只是这一令人担忧的趋势的一个例子，艺术家们的表演被观众向他们投掷物体而打断。</p><p>近几个月来发生的其他事件包括 Drake 在<a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/drake-and-21-savage-announce-huge-2023-its-all-a-blur-tour-3412813">与 21 Savage 巡演</a>期间<a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/drake-calls-out-fan-for-throwing-vape-at-him-on-stage-footage-3472463">两次被人群投掷的物品击中</a>， <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/pink">P!nk</a>在<a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/pink-stunned-as-fan-throws-mothers-ashes-onto-stage-at-bst-hyde-park-3461977">一名粉丝将死去母亲的骨灰扔到伦敦舞台上</a>后感到困惑， <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/harry-styles-hit-eye-thrown-object-vienna-concert-3466448">Harry Styles 被击中在维也纳的</a>一场演出中， <a href="https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a44283921/ava-max-bebe-rexha-attacked-on-stage/">艾娃·麦克斯 (Ava Max) 被跑上舞台的人打了一巴掌</a>。</p><p>其中最令人担忧的是 Bebe Rehxa 的一场演出中发生的事件， <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/bebe-rexha-collapses-on-stage-after-being-struck-in-head-by-fans-phone-at-gig-3457928">一名观众将手机扔到</a>她脸上<a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/bebe-rexha-attacker-reportedly-threw-phone-at-her-head-because-it-would-be-funny-3458236">，因为他认为这会“有趣”，导致</a>这位歌手需要缝针。</p><p> Shortly after the incident with the disposable camera took place, Lacy took to Instagram to call on his fans to stop throwing things at him while he is on stage, and explain how the fad leads to him losing sight of “the beauty of the connection” with his crowd. </p><figure id="attachment_3337844" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-3337844" style="width: 2000px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="size-full wp-image-3337844" src="https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Steve-Lacy-Coachella-2022.jpg" alt="" width="2000" height="1270" srcset="https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Steve-Lacy-Coachella-2022.jpg 2000w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Steve-Lacy-Coachella-2022-400x254.jpg 400w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Steve-Lacy-Coachella-2022-800x508.jpg 800w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Steve-Lacy-Coachella-2022-696x442.jpg 696w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Steve-Lacy-Coachella-2022-1392x884.jpg 1392w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/Steve-Lacy-Coachella-2022-1068x678.jpg 1068w" sizes="(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-3337844" class="wp-caption-text"> Steve Lacy. Credit: Scott Dudelson/Getty Images</figcaption></figure><p> “Shoutout to the people not throwing disposable cameras at me and just coming to catch a vibe and connect. I had a really good time in NOLA last night. I hate that the beauty of the connection I have with so many people in the crowd gets lost when something negative happens,” he wrote (via <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/steve-lacy-smashes-fans-phone-and-storms-offstage-during-new-orleans-concert-3335765"><em>NME</em></a> ). “I don&#39;t believe I owe anyone an apology — maybe I could&#39;ve reacted better? Sure.”</p><p> Elsewhere in his new interview, he recalled how people were initially mad at him for his response, however, in light of recent events, they have now begun to understand his frustration with the incident.</p><p> “People were pissed at me for it, but now they&#39;re like, &#39;He was fuckin&#39; right — y&#39;all shoulda listened to Steve!&#39;” he said. “I didn&#39;t apologise for that shit because I&#39;m not wrong… These moments just go viral. As soon as anything has virality to it, it&#39;s like that&#39;s everything you&#39;ve done. That&#39;s what I hated most about that moment.”</p><p> Highlighting the worrying trend, <a href="https://www.nme.com/features/music-features/crowd-throwing-fans-musicians-injury-3465598"><em>NME</em> explored why fans may want to hurl objects at their favourite performers</a> , but, additionally, how it negatively impacts live shows.</p><p> “The desire for a memorable one-off connection with the pop gods is understandable, particularly in an age when the wealthiest among us can virtually buy a meet-and-spoon with them before the show,” it read. “But it shouldn&#39;t need to be said that risking their personal well-being, the gig itself and a bouncer&#39;s boot in the face for your troubles isn&#39;t worth any amount of TikTok notoriety.”</p><p> “We&#39;ve entered an era where interactions between fan and artist need to revert to respectful boundaries,” it added. “It&#39;s a performance, not a baby shower or disorderly selfie queue, so let the stars get on with dazzling you without the underlying frisson of warzone.”</p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/steve-lacy-on-smashing-fans-camera-on-stage-a-lot-of-kids-dont-know-what-concert-etiquette-is-3480567">Steve Lacy on smashing fan&#39;s camera on stage: “A lot of kids don&#39;t know what concert etiquette is”</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.nme.com">NME</a> .</p> ;
